description:
Comment SLAYGUIDE to get my free 30-page money guide.

Sometimes life choices feel so black and white. Either we’re spending money recklessly or we’re cutting back so much that it pains us to buy ourselves a new pair of shoes.⁠
⁠
But I’m telling you that both are dangerous and the longer it takes you to find the balance, the harder life will be.⁠
⁠
Frugality is usually an emotional response to money trauma.
⁠
Maybe you witnessed your parents or a family member struggling with money and now you hoard yours, because you don’t want to end up like they did.⁠
⁠
This means you may have lost some trust in yourself and your ability to make money throughout your life. I’ve definitely experienced this. Even now I have moments where I fear that all the money I saved and invested will evaporate.⁠
⁠
Sounds crazy, right? But it’s a real fear that I struggle with and work to fight against.⁠
⁠
Whenever I spend money on anything luxurious, it’s a strike I take against this fear. That doesn’t mean I don’t regulate my spending. It just means that I intentionally choose what to spend extra money on and I practice doing so without feeling guilty or anxious.⁠
⁠
Investing definitely helped make me feel more secure.⁠
⁠
I know that I don’t have to be the one to create the money because the market is my partner. If I can’t make more, the market will make it for me. This has helped A LOT.⁠
⁠
So let’s get partnered up so you can take it easy. If you need a place to begin, comment SLAYGUIDE to get my free 30-page guide.

Reposting this since it’s been a year since I moved to Portugal!

$17k for 2 years of health insurance is INSANE and I knew that. But having reliable health insurance when I needed is SO WORTH it to me.

PRO TIP: If you’re quitting a full time job to become self employed, do NOT take COBRA. You can’t deduct it as a business expense since it’s an employer-sponsored plan even though you’re paying in full. Just get your own policy directly from an insurance company or through the marketplace.

I definitely could’ve gone with a cheaper insurance plan. An HMO would’ve cost half.

But if I need a specialist I don’t want to be forced to go to an in-network doctor instead of the one I prefer. I don’t want to ask for a referral every time.

And last but definitely NOT LEAST, I can easily afford this cost. Most people cannot. And just because I can afford it doesn’t make it any less absurd.

I even had my gyno trying to tell me that I should cancel it and just pay her directly. Sounds nice while you’re healthy but not so great if you need life-saving surgery.

description:
Comment FREEDOM below to join my free investing class!

Although I don’t believe that wealth makes you a certain way, I do think it amplifies who you are.

And if you come from a wealthy family that models selfish and unempathetic behavior then you will likely model that behavior as well.

Paul Piff and Dacher Keltner ran several studies looking at whether social class (as measured by wealth, occupational prestige, and education) influences how much we care about the feelings of others.

They found that “less affluent individuals are more likely to report feeling compassion towards others on a regular basis.”

“These findings build upon previous research showing how upper-class individuals are worse at recognizing the emotions of others and less likely to pay attention to people they are interacting with.”

Why does wealth correlate with selfishness?

Piff and his colleagues suspect that the answer may have something to do with how wealth and abundance give us a sense of freedom and independence from others. The less we have to rely on others, the less we may care about their feelings. This leads us to be more self-focused. Another reason has to do with our attitudes towards greed. Like Gordon Gekko, upper-class people may be more likely to endorse the idea that “greed is good.” Piff and his colleagues found that wealthier people are more likely to agree with statements that greed is justified, beneficial, and morally defensible. These attitudes ended up predicting participants’ likelihood of engaging in unethical behavior.”

Source: How Wealth Reduces Compassion, Scientific American

I share this not to say that we will all become selfish if we become wealthy. It’s to be more hyper-aware of this correlation so that you can catch yourself if you start losing perspective.

If anything, I’ve become more hyper-aware of how others are suffering. I’ve become more generous with my donating money and helping out family members.

However, I come from poverty. I know what it’s like to go without.

What if I had been born wealthy?

It’s not a black-and-white issue but one we should all be aware of.

description:
Comment FREEDOM below to join my free investing class!

Have I had bad experiences with employers? Hell yeah. I’ve had 3 professional jobs from 2001-2021 (one before law school & two as an attorney) & all 3 had massive toxic traits. But I don’t base this video on that experience. I base it on 14 years of experience as an employment attorney where I represented employees & studied countless cases. I’ve lost count of how many case holdings I’ve read.

These records are all public & anyone can access them. You can google it. In addition to public records, I also saw all the confidential agreements & arbitrations of the cases I worked on which are not public & I cannot discuss.

Many people think I was only speaking from personal experience when in fact, this is the nature of most workplaces in America. Are there exceptions? Of course there are.

Regardless of whether you agree or disagree with my sentiments, I hope you take away the lesson that we should all be building an FU Fund. I first heard this term from JL Collins, the author of a Simple Path to Wealth.

Why? Because financial independence is something we should all strive for to help build security & stability in good times & especially in bad times. If the last 2 years hasn’t taught us that I don’t know what will. I wouldn’t bank on an employer’s good graces as my safety net.

That doesn’t mean you can’t be friendly at work. Of course you can & you should! But not every colleague deserves your trust & the details about your private life. Use your judgement & be really picky about who you confide in.

DO NOT ever think that HR is your friend. They’re there to represent the company, PERIOD. Many HR managers agreed in the comments of this video so keep that in mind.

FU Fund means saying FU to anything or anyone that steals your peace & all it takes is one new manager or coworker to ruin a perfectly fine work environment. Don’t ever get so comfortable you forget to CYA because I GUARANTEE you your boss & your company is doing just that.

When I tell you that investing is all about letting your money clock in and out for you, this is what I mean.

This little account that I started in 2011 is my ride or die. It’s the one I’m proudest of because I’ve had it the longest. It shows me every day the power of compound interest.

When I started this account, I didn’t know shit about investing. But thankfully I knew enough to keep investing and to leave it alone. And today that account will provide me with all the security I need for traditional retirement.

But I haven’t stopped there. NOPE. I have two more accounts that will fund my EARLY retirement because I have no desire to work until I’m 60. That’s a personal choice I’ve been blessed to make thanks to investing.

As you can see this is not get-rich-quick overnight pie-in-the-sky BS. So if you’re about this, then that’s what I’ll be teaching here.

latest_comments.comments: Portugal is where I want to retire too 😢

Mmmm..... there is some rose-colored glasses optics going on here.  I lived in Portugal for a year.  It was fine.... for those who were retired,  financially independent,  or who work remotely full-time. The grass isn't greener.  Portugal has its own government issues,  incredulous bureaucracy,  no jobs available,  raising home prices and inflation, impossibility of having anything done in an appropriate amount of time,  dog poo, cigarette smoke, domestic violence that is taken to the streets in the middle of the night,  and a general population melancholy that hangs over the country like a cloud since the dictatorship.  Is it lovely country? Yes.  Is the food/coffee/cheese/bread/cholocate/orange juice amazing? Yes.  It's the ocean gorgeous? Yes. Is it nice being able to travel between countries via train? Yes. So then visit and vacation there.  But becoming a resident and living in a different country day-to-day is not easy. It's not fun.  For many it's not worth it.  Portugal does some things right but not everything.  Every country has room for improvement,  progression, and evolution. Don't go there running away from something.  Portugal is not Pure Land, Nirvana, or Shagri-La. Take it from someone who knows.  Don't reinvent the wheel.  DO NOT sell your possessions until you've been in a country for at least a year and are certain. It's MUCH cheaper to store it than to have to return home just to have to replace it all.  Make sure you have a cemented steam of income and that your employer is willing to pay foreign labor taxes.  A lot of my fellow Expats lost their jobs while there due to employers trimming the fat. Make more than one scouting trip to various cities of your new chosen country.  Listen genuinely to those with opinions on both side of the coin,  remembering that NO country is perfect. Brexit and France's recent election should be examples of that.
